Segmentation homonymy is very common, as word forms can often be segmented in several different ways. This phenomenon is widespread in Yakut for disyllabic verbal roots that have a fossilized productive affix in the last syllable. For example, the form *кэбис* can be analyzed as a lexical root meaning 'to throw' or as *кэп* (to hit, to strike a counter-blow) + reflexive affix *-ис*.

There is a small number of words that simultaneously express both verbal and nominal meanings, for example *санаа* (to think; thought), *тыын* (to breath; breath), *тот* (to get satiated; satiated), *тоҥ* (to freeze; frozen),  *аас* (to starve; hunger),  *саат* (to be ashamed, shame), [Kharitonov, 1947:168-169].


Homonyms can occur in the lexicon when a lexical root is associated with more than one stem. For example, the root *санаа* can be interpreted as a verbal root (the second person imperative form of the verb "to think") or as a nominal (the nominative singular form of the noun "thought"). Affixation often helps resolve this type of lexical homonymy, since stem types impose restrictions on the affixes that can be attached to them.

## Grammatical Categories

When isolating categories of words , they try to take into account the entire set of semantic, syntactic and morphological features inherent in words in a given language. Such a detailed classification of words, revealing their lexical and grammatical features,

In the Yakut language words can be grouped according to their relation to inflection forms. In this regard, Ubryatova et. [REFERENCE] propose to classify all words of the Yakut language into the following three large groups:
1. Words of the nominal type (take declensions);
2. Words of the verbal type (can be conjugated);
3. Unchangeable words (with some exceptions they are not inflected)

Ubryatova et al. note that, although that division is approximate, inflection forms in the Yakut language, seem to be a fairly stable and characteristic grammatical feature.

Nominal type: nouns, adjectives, numerals and pronouns.
Verbal type: verbs, participles and converbs.
Unchangeable words: adverbs, interjections, imitatives, figuratives, postpositions, modals, conjunctions, auxiliars and particles.

The role of a word in a sentence, its connection with certain grammatical categories or concepts, as well as the nature of its grammatical changes, largely depend on the nature of its basic lexical meaning. For example, the category and forms of tense are inherent only to those words that express the concept of an action or state, and case to words expressing the concept of an object [[1:36]](#bibliography).

According to Ubryatova et al., proper names should not be considered a special grammatical category but rather a special semantic class of nouns [1:107-108]. The authors argue that proper nouns do not have a distinct grammatical form of expression (they can only take individual diminutive forms and are written with a capital letter). Therefore, proper names should be listed in the lexicon as nouns. However, since their theoretical number is infinite—particularly given the presence of many proper nouns in the Russian language within Yakut texts—the task of their analysis can be delegated to the subsequent transducers in the morphological pipeline (see Morphological Pipeline).


